\subsection{Understanding the Results}{

\strong{P-value}: If p < 0.05, at least one measurement is significantly different
\itemize{
\item p < 0.001: Very strong evidence of differences
\item p < 0.01: Strong evidence of differences
\item p < 0.05: Moderate evidence of differences
\item p > 0.05: No significant differences found
}

\strong{Kendall's W} (Effect size: How consistent is the pattern?):
\itemize{
\item < 0.1: Negligible agreement/effect
\item 0.1 - 0.3: Weak agreement
\item 0.3 - 0.5: Moderate agreement
\item 0.5 or higher: Strong agreement
}

\strong{Mean Ranks}:
\itemize{
\item Higher mean rank = measurement tends to have higher values
\item Lower mean rank = measurement tends to have lower values
\item Compare mean ranks to see which measurements stand out
}
}

\subsection{When to Use This}{

Use the Friedman test when:
\itemize{
\item You have 3 or more related measurements from the same subjects
\item Your data is not normally distributed
\item You have ordinal data (ratings, rankings)
\item You want a robust alternative to repeated-measures ANOVA
\item You're comparing multiple ratings by the same respondents
}
